2.2 Comments
============

You can write comments in a Texinfo file by using the â€˜@commentâ€™
command, which may be abbreviated to â€˜@câ€™.  Such comments are for a
person looking at the Texinfo source file.  All the text on a line that
follows either â€˜@commentâ€™ or â€˜@câ€™ is a comment; the rest of the line
does not appear in the visible output.  (To be precise, the character
after the â€˜@câ€™ or â€˜@commentâ€™ must be something other than a dash or
alphanumeric, or it will be taken as part of the command.)

   Often, you can write the â€˜@commentâ€™ or â€˜@câ€™ in the middle of a line,
and only the text that follows after the â€˜@commentâ€™ or â€˜@câ€™ command does
not appear; but some commands, such as â€˜@settitleâ€™, work on a whole
line.  You cannot use â€˜@commentâ€™ or â€˜@câ€™ within a line beginning with
such a command.

   In cases of nested command invocations, complicated macro
definitions, etc., â€˜@câ€™ and â€˜@commentâ€™ may provoke an error when
processing with TeX.  Therefore, you can also use the â€˜DELâ€™ character
(ASCII 127 decimal, 0x7f hex, 0177 octal) as a true TeX comment
character (catcode 14, in TeX internals).  Everything on the line after
the â€˜DELâ€™ will be ignored and the next line will be merged.

   You can also have long stretches of text ignored by the Texinfo
processors with the â€˜@ignoreâ€™ and â€˜@end ignoreâ€™ commands.  Write each of
these commands on a line of its own, starting each command at the
beginning of the line.  Text between these two commands does not appear
in the processed output.  You can use â€˜@ignoreâ€™ and â€˜@end ignoreâ€™ for
writing comments.  (For some caveats regarding nesting of such commands,
*note* Conditional Nesting::.)


