2.5.2 â€˜@setfilenameâ€™: Set the Output File Name
----------------------------------------------

The â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ line specifies the name of the output file to be
generated by â€˜texi2anyâ€™.  This command is ignored for TeX formatting.
When present, it should be the first Texinfo command (that is, after
â€˜\input texinfoâ€™).  Write the â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ command at the beginning of
a line and follow it on the same line by the Info file name.

     @setfilename INFO-FILE-NAME

   The name must be different from the name of the Texinfo file.  There
are two conventions for choosing the name: you can either remove the
extension (such as â€˜.texiâ€™) entirely from the input file name, or
(recommended) replace it with the â€˜.infoâ€™ extension.  It is not advised
to base the â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ name on a entirely different name than the
input file name.

   When a â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ line is present, the Texinfo processors ignore
everything written before the â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ line.  This is why the very
first line of the file (the â€˜\inputâ€™ line) does not show up in the
output.

   If there is no â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ line, â€˜texi2anyâ€™ uses the input file
name to determine the output name (*note* Minimum::).  The â€˜\inputâ€™ line
is still ignored in this processing, as well as leading blank lines.

   When producing another output format, â€˜texi2anyâ€™ will replace any
final extension with the output format-specific extension (â€˜htmlâ€™ when
generating HTML, for example), or add a dot followed by the extension
(â€˜.htmlâ€™ for HTML) if the given name has no extension.

   @-commands are not allowed in â€˜@setfilenameâ€™, except for â€˜@@â€™, â€˜@{â€™,
â€˜@}â€™ and associated @-commands such as â€˜@atchar{}â€™.

   â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ used to be required by the Texinfo processors and some
other programs.  This should not be the case any more; â€˜@setfilenameâ€™
can be omitted.  If the Texinfo input is processed from standard input,
without an input file name to deduce the base file name from,
â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ could still be relevant.  This is not the only way,
however: â€˜--outputâ€™ option specifies the output file name on the
â€˜texi2anyâ€™ command-line (*note* Invoking texi2any::).

   Although an explicit â€˜.infoâ€™ extension is preferable, some operating
systems cannot handle long file names.  You can run into a problem even
when the file name you specify is itself short enough.  This occurs
because the Info formatters split a long Info file into short indirect
subfiles, and name them by appending â€˜-1â€™, â€˜-2â€™, ..., â€˜-10â€™, â€˜-11â€™, and
so on, to the original file name.  (*Note* Tag and Split Files::.)  The
subfile name â€˜texinfo.info-10â€™, for example, is too long for old systems
with a 14-character limit on filenames; so the Info file name for this
document could be â€˜texinfoâ€™ rather than â€˜texinfo.infoâ€™ on such a system.
â€˜@setfilenameâ€™ is a way to specify an alternative name.


