2.8.3 â€˜@titlefontâ€™, â€˜@centerâ€™, and â€˜@spâ€™
----------------------------------------

You can also use the â€˜@titlefontâ€™, â€˜@spâ€™, and â€˜@centerâ€™ commands to
create a title page for a printed document.

   Use the â€˜@titlefontâ€™ command to select a large font suitable for the
title itself.  You can use â€˜@titlefontâ€™ more than once if you have an
especially long title.

   For HTML output, each â€˜@titlefontâ€™ command produces an â€˜<h1>â€™
heading, but the HTML document â€˜<title>â€™ is not affected.  For that, you
could put a â€˜@settitleâ€™ command before the â€˜@titlefontâ€™ command (*note*
@settitle::).

   For example:

     @titlefont{Texinfo}

   Use the â€˜@centerâ€™ command at the beginning of a line to center the
remaining text on that line.  Thus,

     @center @titlefont{Texinfo}

centers the title, which in this example is "Texinfo" printed in the
title font.

   Use the â€˜@spâ€™ command to insert vertical space.  For example:

     @sp 2

This inserts two blank lines on the printed page.  (*Note* @sp::, for
more information about the â€˜@spâ€™ command.)

   A template for this method looks like this:

     @titlepage
     @sp 10
     @center @titlefont{NAME-OF-MANUAL-WHEN-PRINTED}
     @sp 2
     @center SUBTITLE-IF-ANY
     @sp 2
     @center AUTHOR
     ...
     @end titlepage

   The spacing of the example fits an 8.5 by 11 inch manual.


