     environments (e.g., â€˜@quotationâ€™), commands that read a whole line
     as their argument (e.g., â€˜@spâ€™), and plenty of others.  For the
     complete list of commands that are allowed, and their expansion for
     HTML identifiers and file names, *note* HTML Xref Command
     Expansion::.

   â€¢ A node name may not start with a left parenthesis preceding a right
     parenthesis, as in â€˜(not)allowedâ€™, since this syntax is used to
     specify an external manual.

   â€¢ Unfortunately, you cannot reliably use periods, commas, or colons
     within a node name; these can confuse some Info readers.
     â€˜texi2anyâ€™ quotes problematic node names and labels by default, but
     some Info readers do not recognize this syntax.  Node name and
     label quoting causes â€˜DELâ€™ characters (â€˜CTRL-?â€™, character number
     127, often rendered as â€˜^?â€™) to appear around the name.  To remove
     node names and labels quoting, you can set the customization
     variable â€˜INFO_SPECIAL_CHARS_QUOTEâ€™ to â€˜0â€™ (*note* Other
     Customization Variables::).

     â€˜texi2anyâ€™ warns about such problematic usage in node names, menu
     items, and cross-references.  If you don't want to see the
     warnings, you can set the customization variable
     â€˜INFO_SPECIAL_CHARS_WARNINGâ€™ to â€˜0â€™ (*note* Other Customization
