structure of the document; even to nodes in a different Info file.
However, the â€˜texi2anyâ€™ implicit pointer creation feature (*note* Writing
a Node::) and GNU Emacs Texinfo mode updating commands work only to
create menus of subordinate nodes in a hierarchically structured
document.  In a hierarchically structured document, it is much better to
use cross-references to refer to arbitrary nodes.

   In Info, a user selects a node with the â€˜mâ€™ (â€˜Info-menuâ€™) command.
The menu entry name is what the user types after the â€˜mâ€™ command.  In
the HTML output, the â€˜accesskeyâ€™ attribute is used with the values
â€˜1â€™...â€˜9â€™ for the first nine entries.  This allows people using web
browsers to follow the first menu entries using (typically) â€˜M-DIGITâ€™,
e.g., â€˜M-1â€™ for the first entry.


