6.1.2 â€˜@codeâ€™{SAMPLE-CODE}
--------------------------

Use the â€˜@codeâ€™ command to indicate text that is a piece of a program
and which consists of entire syntactic tokens.  Enclose the text in
braces.

   Thus, you should use â€˜@codeâ€™ for an expression in a program, for the
name of a variable or function used in a program, or for a keyword in a
programming language.

   Use â€˜@codeâ€™ for command names in languages that resemble programming
languages, such as Texinfo.  For example, â€˜@codeâ€™ and â€˜@sampâ€™ are
produced by writing â€˜@code{@@code}â€™ and â€˜@code{@@samp}â€™ in the Texinfo
source, respectively.

   It is incorrect to alter the case of a word inside a â€˜@codeâ€™ command
when it appears at the beginning of a sentence.  Most computer languages
are case sensitive.  In C, for example, â€˜Printfâ€™ is different from the
identifier â€˜printfâ€™, and most likely is a misspelling of it.  Even in
languages which are not case sensitive, it is confusing to a human
reader to see identifiers spelled in different ways.  Pick one spelling
and always use that.  If you do not want to start a sentence with a
command name written all in lowercase, you should rearrange the
sentence.

   The â€˜@codeâ€™ argument is typeset in a typewriter (monospace) font.
where the output format allows this.  For example,

     The function returns @code{nil}.

