     The function returns â€˜nilâ€™.

   Here are some cases for which it is preferable _not_ to use â€˜@codeâ€™:

   â€¢ For shell command names, such as â€˜lsâ€™ (use â€˜@commandâ€™).

   â€¢ For environment variables, such as â€˜TEXINPUTSâ€™ (use â€˜@envâ€™).

   â€¢ For shell options, such as â€˜-câ€™, when such options stand alone (use
     â€˜@optionâ€™).

   â€¢ An entire shell command often looks better if written using â€˜@sampâ€™
     rather than â€˜@codeâ€™.  In this case, the rule is to choose the more
     pleasing format.

   â€¢ For a string of characters shorter than a syntactic token.  For
     example, if you are writing about â€˜goto-châ€™, which is just a part
     of the name for the â€˜goto-charâ€™ Emacs Lisp function, you should use
     â€˜@sampâ€™.

   â€¢ In general, when writing about the characters used in a token; for
     example, do not use â€˜@codeâ€™ when you are explaining what letters or
     printable symbols can be used in the names of functions.  (Use
     â€˜@sampâ€™.)  Also, you should not use â€˜@codeâ€™ to mark text that is
     considered input to programs unless the input is written in a
     language that is like a programming language.  For example, you
     should not use â€˜@codeâ€™ for the keystroke commands of GNU Emacs (use
     â€˜@kbdâ€™ instead) although you may use â€˜@codeâ€™ for the names of the
     Emacs Lisp functions that the keystroke commands invoke.

   By default, TeX will consider breaking lines at â€˜-â€™ and â€˜_â€™
characters within â€˜@codeâ€™ and related commands.  This can be controlled
with â€˜@allowcodebreaksâ€™ (*note* @allowcodebreaks::).  In the HTML output
breaking lines is up to the browser's behavior.  For Info, it seems
better never to make such breaks.

