7.12 â€˜@noindentâ€™: Omitting Indentation
======================================

An example or other inclusion can break a paragraph into segments.
Ordinarily, the formatters indent text that follows an example as a new
paragraph.  You can prevent this on a case-by-case basis by writing
â€˜@noindentâ€™ at the beginning of a line, preceding the continuation text.
You can also disable indentation for all paragraphs globally with
â€˜@paragraphindentâ€™ (*note* @paragraphindent::).

   Here is an example showing how to eliminate the normal indentation of
the text after an â€˜@exampleâ€™, a common situation:

     @example
     This is an example
     @end example

     @noindent
     This line is not indented.  As you can see, the
     beginning of the line is fully flush left with the
     line that follows after it.

produces:

          This is an example

     This line is not indented.  As you can see, the
     beginning of the line is fully flush left with the
     line that follows after it.

   The standard usage of â€˜@noindentâ€™ is just as above: at the beginning
of what would otherwise be a paragraph, to eliminate the indentation
that normally happens there.  It can either be followed by text or be on
a line by itself.  There is no reason to use it in other contexts, such
as in the middle of a paragraph or inside an environment (*note*
Quotations and Examples::).

   You can control the number of blank lines in the Info file output by
adjusting the input as desired: a line containing just â€˜@noindentâ€™ does
not generate a blank line, and neither does an â€˜@endâ€™ line for an
environment.

   Do not put braces after a â€˜@noindentâ€™ command; they are not used,
since â€˜@noindentâ€™ is a command used outside of paragraphs (*note* Command
Syntax::).


