10.6.1 â€˜@syncodeindexâ€™: Combining Indices Using â€˜@codeâ€™
-------------------------------------------------------

When you want to combine functions and concepts into one index, you
should index the functions with â€˜@findexâ€™ and index the concepts with
â€˜@cindexâ€™, and use the â€˜@syncodeindexâ€™ command to redirect the function
index entries into the concept index.

   The â€˜@syncodeindexâ€™ command takes two arguments; they are the name of
the index to redirect, and the name of the index to redirect it to.  The
template looks like this:

     @syncodeindex FROM TO

   For this purpose, the indices are given two-letter names:

â€˜cpâ€™
     Concept index
â€˜fnâ€™
     Function index
â€˜kyâ€™
     Key index
â€˜pgâ€™
     Program index
â€˜tpâ€™
     Data type index
â€˜vrâ€™
     Variable index

   Write a â€˜@syncodeindexâ€™ command before or shortly after the
end-of-header line at the beginning of a Texinfo file.  For example, to
merge a function index with a concept index, write the following:

     @syncodeindex fn cp

This causes all entries designated for the function index to merge in
with the concept index instead.

   To merge both a variable index and a function index into a concept
index, write the following:

     @syncodeindex vr cp
     @syncodeindex fn cp

   The â€˜@syncodeindexâ€™ command puts all the entries from the 'from'
index (the redirected index) into the â€˜@codeâ€™ font, overriding whatever
default font is used by the index to which the entries are now directed.
This way, if you direct function names from a function index into a
concept index, all the function names are printed in the â€˜@codeâ€™ font as
you would expect.


