11.2 Inserting Quote Characters
===============================

As explained in the early section on general Texinfo input conventions
(*note* Conventions::), Texinfo source files use the ASCII character â€˜`â€™
(96 decimal) to produce a left quote ('), and ASCII â€˜'â€™ (39 decimal) to
produce a right quote (').  Doubling these input characters (â€˜``â€™ and
â€˜''â€™) produces double quotes (" and ").  These are the conventions used
by TeX.

   In examples of computer code, however, â€˜`â€™ and â€˜'â€™ produce typical
renderings for these ASCII characters: the backtick character
(standalone grave accent) and undirected single quote respectively.  In
the past, directed glyphs were used by default in TeX output.  Texinfo
provides these commands to choose between these alternate renderings:

â€˜@codequoteundirected ON-OFFâ€™
     Set to â€˜offâ€™ to output the â€˜'â€™ character in code environments as
     the right curly single quote.

â€˜@codequotebacktick ON-OFFâ€™
     Set to â€˜offâ€™ to output the â€˜`â€™ character in code environments as
     the left curly single quote.

   If you want these settings for only part of the document,
â€˜@codequote... onâ€™ will restore the normal behavior, as in
â€˜@codequoteundirected onâ€™.

   These settings affect â€˜@codeâ€™, â€˜@exampleâ€™, â€˜@kbdâ€™, â€˜@sampâ€™, â€˜@verbâ€™,
and â€˜@verbatimâ€™.  *Note* Useful Highlighting::.

   Unfortunately, some document viewers will mangle the directed quote
characters when copying and pasting.  (The free PDF reader â€˜xpdfâ€™ works
fine, but other PDF readers, both free and nonfree, have problems.)

   This feature can also be controlled by using â€˜@setâ€™ and â€˜@clearâ€™ on
the corresponding variables â€˜txicodequoteundirectedâ€™ and
â€˜txicodequotebacktickâ€™.


