18.3 Format with â€˜texâ€™/â€˜texindexâ€™
=================================

You can do the basic formatting of a Texinfo file with the shell command
â€˜texâ€™ followed by the name of the Texinfo file.  For example:

     tex foo.texi

TeX will produce a â€œDVI fileâ€ as well as several auxiliary files
containing information for indices, cross-references, etc.  The DVI file
(for â€œDeVice Independentâ€ file) can be printed on virtually any device,
perhaps after a further conversion (see the previous section).

   The â€˜texâ€™ formatting command itself does not sort the indices; it
writes an output file of unsorted index data.  To generate a printed
index after running the â€˜texâ€™ command, you first need a sorted index to
work from.  The â€˜texindexâ€™ command sorts indices.  (â€˜texi2dviâ€™,
described in the previous section, runs â€˜texâ€™ and â€˜texindexâ€™ as
necessary.)

   â€˜texâ€™ outputs unsorted index files under names following a standard
convention: the name of your main input file with any â€˜.texiâ€™ or similar
extension replaced by the two letter index name.  For example, the raw
index output files for the input file â€˜foo.texiâ€™ would be, by default,
â€˜foo.cpâ€™, â€˜foo.vrâ€™, â€˜foo.fnâ€™, â€˜foo.tpâ€™, â€˜foo.pgâ€™ and â€˜foo.kyâ€™.  Those
are exactly the arguments to give to â€˜texindexâ€™.

   Instead of specifying all the unsorted index file names explicitly,
it's typical to use â€˜??â€™ as shell wildcards and give the command in this
form:

     texindex foo.??

This command will run â€˜texindexâ€™ on all the unsorted index files,
including any two letter indices that you have defined yourself using
â€˜@defindexâ€™ or â€˜@defcodeindexâ€™.  You can safely run â€˜texindex foo.??â€™
even if there are files with two letter extensions that are not index
files, such as â€˜foo.elâ€™.  The â€˜texindexâ€™ command reports but otherwise
ignores such files.

   For each file specified, â€˜texindexâ€™ generates a sorted index file
whose name is made by appending â€˜sâ€™ to the input file name; for example,
â€˜foo.cpsâ€™ is made from â€˜foo.cpâ€™.  The â€˜@printindexâ€™ command looks for a
file with that name (*note* Printing Indices & Menus::).  TeX does not
read the raw index output file, and â€˜texindexâ€™ does not alter it.

   After you have sorted the indices, you need to rerun â€˜texâ€™ on the
Texinfo file.  This regenerates the output file, this time with
up-to-date index entries.

   Finally, you may need to run â€˜texâ€™ one more time, to get the page
numbers in the cross-references correct.

   To summarize, this is a five-step process.  (Alternatively, it's a
one-step process: run â€˜texi2dviâ€™; see the previous section.)

  1. Run â€˜texâ€™ on your Texinfo file.  This generates a DVI file (with
     undefined cross-references and no indices), and the raw index files
     (with two letter extensions).

  2. Run â€˜texindexâ€™ on the raw index files.  This creates the
     corresponding sorted index files (with three letter extensions).

  3. Run â€˜texâ€™ again on your Texinfo file.  This regenerates the DVI
     file, this time with indices and defined cross-references, but with
     page numbers for the cross-references from the previous run,
     generally incorrect.

  4. Sort the indices again, with â€˜texindexâ€™.

  5. Run â€˜texâ€™ one last time.  This time the correct page numbers are
     written for the cross-references.

   To generate PDF, you can run the â€˜pdftexâ€™ program instead of plain
â€˜texâ€™.  That is, run â€˜pdftex foo.texiâ€™ instead of â€˜tex foo.texiâ€™ in the
examples above.

