21.2 HTML Splitting
===================

When splitting output at nodes (which is the default), â€˜texi2anyâ€™ writes
HTML output into (basically) one output file per Texinfo source â€˜@nodeâ€™.

   Each output file name is the node name with spaces replaced by â€˜-â€™'s
and special characters changed to â€˜_â€™ followed by their code point in
hex (*note* HTML Xref::).  This is to make it portable and easy to use as
a file name.  In the unusual case of two different nodes having the same
name after this treatment, they are written consecutively to the same
file, with HTML anchors so each can be referred to independently.

   If â€˜texi2anyâ€™ is run on a system which does not distinguish case in
file names, nodes which are the same except for case (e.g., â€˜indexâ€™ and
â€˜Indexâ€™) will also be folded into the same output file with anchors.
You can also pretend to be on a case insensitive filesystem by setting
the customization variable â€˜CASE_INSENSITIVE_FILENAMESâ€™.

   It is also possible to split at chapters or sections with â€˜--splitâ€™
(*note* Invoking texi2any::).  In that case, the file names are
constructed after the name of the node associated with the relevant
sectioning command.  Also, unless â€˜--no-node-filesâ€™ is specified, a
redirection file is output for every node in order to more reliably
